<DOC><DOCNO> AP880614-0135 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 2100EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-AshlandTrial     06-14 0218</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Ashland Trial,0223</SECOND><HEAD>Ashland to Appeal $70 Million Award to Two Former Vice Presidents</HEAD><DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ashland Oil Inc. says it will appeal anearly $70 million award to two former vice presidents who claimedthey were illegally fired for refusing to bribe foreign officialsor cover up such bribes.   A U.S. District Court jury Friday awarded Bill McKay $44,594,936and Harry D. Williams $24,980,431.   Ashland, in a prepared statement, said it was ``verydisappointed by the verdict,'' which it said was not supported bythe evidence, and planned to appeal.   The company maintained throughout the trial that payments tosecure Arab oil during the 1970s and 1980s went to men of influencewho were not government officials.   The jury decided that three of the men were government officialswhen they were paid and that at least two cases of briberyoccurred, putting the case under the Racketeering InfluenceCorruption Act (RICO), a federal law usually aimed at organizedcrime.   Ashlandm also maintained the men were fired for ineffective workand claimed the plaintiffs conspired to get fired in order to sueAshland.   The jury's decision came after a 35-day trial. Named asdefendants were the company, former chairman Orin Atkins, currentchairman John R. Hall, vice chairman Robert McCowan and vicepresident Dick Spears.</TEXT></DOC>